05449nam a2200697Ia 9780791480038DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97807914800387 a10.1515/97807914800382doi  a(DE-B1597)683658  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHT1521b.R234 2007eb 7aSOC0310002bisacsh04a305.822200aRace and Epistemologies of Ignorance /ced. by Shannon Sullivan, Nancy Tuana. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (282 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series, Philosophy and Race00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tTheorizing Ignorance -- tWhite Ignorance -- tEpistemologies of Ignorance -- tEver Not Quite -- tStrategic Ignorance -- tDenying Relationality -- tManaging Ignorance -- tSituating Ignorance -- tRace Problems, Unknown Publics, Paralysis, and Faith -- tWhite Ignorance and Colonial Oppression -- tJohn Dewey, W. E. B. Du Bois, and Alain Locke -- tSocial Ordering and the Systematic Production of Ignorance -- tThe Power of Ignorance -- tOn Needing Not to Know and Forgetting What One Never Knew -- tOn the Absence of Biology in Philosophical Considerations of Race -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOffering a wide variety of philosophical approaches to the neglected philosophical problem of ignorance, this groundbreaking collection builds on Charles Mills's claim that racism involves an inverted epistemology, an epistemology of ignorance. Contributors explore how different forms of ignorance linked to race are produced and sustained and what role they play in promoting racism and white privilege. They argue that the ignorance that underpins racism is not a simple gap in knowledge, the accidental result of an epistemological oversight. In the case of racial oppression, ignorance often is actively produced for purposes of domination and exploitation. But as these essays demonstrate, ignorance is not simply a tool of oppression wielded by the powerful. It can also be a strategy for survival, an important tool for people of color to wield against white privilege and white supremacy. The book concludes that understanding ignorance and the politics of such ignorance should be a key element of epistemological and social/political analyses, for it has the potential to reveal the role of power in the construction of what is known and provide a lens for the political values at work in knowledge practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRace relations. 0aSocial epistemology. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh1 aAlcoff, Linda Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernasconi, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCode, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCormier, Harvey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFullerton, Stephanie Malia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoagland, Sarah Lucia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargonis, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, Charles W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOutlaw, Lucius T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpelman, Elizabeth V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSullivan, Shannon, econtributor.4ctb4